1784402140329992	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErAQ		item.create	bn-qsu	{"description":"Problem\nSippycup currently exposes capable individual commands, but the operator must manually keep target scope, traffic limits, captures, timeouts, cleanup, and evidence aligned. That is error-prone precisely when a test becomes interesting.\n\nOutcome\nAdd `sippycup campaign plan|run MANIFEST` around a versioned YAML manifest. The manifest describes authorized hostnames/IPs/CIDRs, SIP transports and ports, allowed media ranges, test identities by secret reference, expected capabilities, selected cases, maximum calls/CPS/concurrency/packets/duration, stop conditions, and evidence policy.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- `plan` validates the schema, resolves hostnames once, freezes the resulting addresses, rejects destinations outside scope, expands cases, computes an upper traffic bound, and prints every command/capture filter without sending traffic.\n- `run` creates a unique UTC run directory, records the frozen plan and tool/image versions, starts target-scoped capture, executes each bounded step with deadlines, and always cleans up children/qdiscs on success, failure, or SIGINT.\n- Secrets enter through environment variables, file descriptors, or an external command contract; never serialize secret values into manifests, argv, logs, or reports.\n- Emit a small append-only JSON event stream so future analyzers and UIs can consume progress without scraping terminal text.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- Empty scope, unresolved placeholders, scope drift after DNS resolution, missing stop conditions, and any requested value above the manifest budget fail before network traffic.\n- Plan output is deterministic and clearly states exact targets plus maximum calls, packets, concurrency, and duration.\n- A checked-in loopback example completes capture and a one-call SIPp scenario; Ctrl-C leaves no child process or network impairment behind.\n- Schema versioning, actionable validation errors, shell completion, unit tests, and an end-to-end isolated-container test are included.\n- Existing `capture`, `preflight`, `report`, and `selftest` commands remain usable independently.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nNo arbitrary shell embedded in manifests, no distributed controller, no cloud service, and no implicit credential discovery. Running an active case always requires an explicit manifest; sample values remain non-routable.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","foundation","safety","orchestration"],"size":"l","title":"Build a declarative, safety-gated campaign runner","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:UWvA3jWX4L_RMOxTJ2JR1BNOChibBYM8LUe8Y4dh_Uo
1784402161818649	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErAg		item.create	bn-1da	{"description":"Problem\nThe current report presents useful facts but leaves the operator to decide whether a call was correct. Ferivox needs repeatable black-box verdicts about signaling, direct media behavior, and teardown—not screenshots interpreted by eye.\n\nOutcome\nImplement `sippycup assert CAPTURE --expect EXPECTATIONS.yaml` as a read-only protocol oracle with stable human and JSON output. It reconstructs SIP dialogs and RTP/RTCP streams, correlates offer/answer SDP with observed media, and evaluates explicit invariants.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- Model dialogs using Call-ID, tags, CSeq, Via branches, routes, transaction retransmissions, and provisional/final responses; represent ambiguity as `unknown`, never silently pass it.\n- Map each SDP media section and payload type to observed RTP/RTCP five-tuples and SSRCs across re-INVITEs/UPDATEs.\n- Check setup/teardown completeness, response timing, retransmission storms, early media, bidirectional media, expected codecs and RFC 4733 events, sequence loss/duplication/reordering, interarrival jitter, SSRC/payload changes, media before answer, and media after BYE.\n- Enforce direct-path expectations: flag signaling/media sent to an address outside the frozen scope and distinguish a negotiated relay from an unexplained third party.\n- Use TShark field/JSON output initially; isolate parsing behind typed internal records so a native parser can replace it later.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- Exit codes distinguish pass, assertion failure, malformed expectations, unreadable capture, and inconclusive analysis.\n- JSON has a versioned schema with per-dialog/per-stream evidence including frame numbers and timestamps; terminal output links every failure to that evidence.\n- Fixtures cover UDP/TCP SIP, IPv4/IPv6, retransmissions, early media, renegotiation, one-way RTP, loss/reorder, DTMF, unexpected endpoints, and packets after teardown.\n- A capture with no RTP does not pass a bidirectional-media expectation; encrypted media is reported without pretending payload quality was inspected.\n- Authorization headers and decoded audio are excluded from default output.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nThis is a capture oracle, not a full RFC conformance proof or an IDS. Initial scope is one dialog with ordinary forks represented explicitly; complex B2BUA correlation may be added only with reliable identifiers.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","analysis","rtp","oracle"],"size":"xl","title":"Turn PCAPs into executable call-path verdicts","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:p1m2g0Q9bfs44DhBq1nSU4Frgt8nwoi5P1bbAMGNAW0
1784402181643418	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErAw		item.create	bn-3oz	{"description":"Problem\nPacket counters can prove that RTP moved, but not that intelligible, correctly timed audio survived codec handling, buffering, model processing, or an echo path. Subjective listening is slow and non-reproducible.\n\nOutcome\nAdd `sippycup media generate|send|analyze` for deterministic, machine-detectable audio canaries and RFC 4733 events. A test call should produce defensible measurements of media continuity and round-trip behavior without requiring Ferivox instrumentation.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- Generate short seeded canaries containing direction-specific chirps/pseudorandom tone codes, calibrated silence, amplitude steps, and an optional synthetic phrase. Preserve a manifest of expected marker positions and levels.\n- Encode and packetize at least PCMU, PCMA, and G.722 using existing SoX/GStreamer/FFmpeg components; integrate with SIPp RTP streaming/PCAP play.\n- Detect returned markers by cross-correlation and report acquisition time, round-trip latency, dropouts, clipping, gross gain change, channel swaps, duration error, and unexpected energy during silence.\n- Generate and validate RFC 4733 DTMF separately, including negotiated payload type, marker/end bits, duration, redundant ending packets, sequence continuity, and digit order.\n- Feed transport facts to the PCAP assertion schema and keep decoded WAV output opt-in because it may contain voice.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- A loopback fixture detects every marker and digit and reports latency within one packetization interval.\n- Seeded netem fixtures for delay, burst loss, duplication, and reordering produce repeatable measurements and expected failures.\n- Codec round trips have documented tolerance bands; unsupported/encrypted payloads return `not measurable`, never a fabricated quality score.\n- Tests detect one-way audio, all-zero payload, clipped audio, missing DTMF endings, and audio continuing beyond the expected window.\n- Generated fixtures are tiny, deterministic, license-clean, and reproducible from source.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nDo not label heuristic results as MOS/PESQ/POLQA and do not claim one-way latency without synchronized remote markers. No speech recognition dependency is required for the first release.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","media","qoe","rtp"],"size":"l","title":"Build a deterministic RTP and audio canary oracle"}	blake3:dZonpc2iJIQtFlIxEi_iYsyuBW71ATyq091YPF8pJ_Q
1784402202043875	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErBA		item.create	bn-2bt	{"description":"Problem\nTransport, codec, address family, DTMF mode, call state, hangup side, and impairment combinations explode rapidly. Handwritten matrices either miss interactions or waste time on redundant cases.\n\nOutcome\nImplement `sippycup matrix` to turn manifest factors and constraints into a small, auditable covering array plus event-sequence suite. Default to pairwise coverage, with optional higher strength for selected risk-heavy factors.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- Factors include signaling transport, IPv4/IPv6, codec/ptime, RTP/SRTP mode, DTMF mode, early media, hold/re-INVITE, initiator of teardown, call duration class, NAT behavior, and impairment profile.\n- Support declarative constraints such as “TLS requires this port”, “codec X is unavailable with profile Y”, and “SRTP case requires keying mode Z”. Reject unsatisfiable models with a useful explanation.\n- Use a deterministic IPOG/covering-array implementation or a small maintained library; add sequence-covering generation for ordered call actions such as hold, resume, DTMF, re-INVITE, and hangup.\n- Emit runnable campaign cases, a coverage ledger of every t-way tuple, excluded combinations with reasons, estimated traffic budget, and a risk-weighted execution order.\n- Allow mandatory handpicked cases alongside generated cases and ingest historical failures as priority hints without changing coverage claims.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- Property tests prove every permitted pair appears in at least one generated case; constrained pairs are correctly excluded and reported.\n- Output is deterministic for a seed and materially smaller than the Cartesian product on the supplied Ferivox example.\n- Every generated case compiles through campaign `plan` and remains within aggregate call/packet/duration budgets.\n- Sequence coverage distinguishes action order and includes failure-recovery paths.\n- Reports state achieved coverage honestly when budget truncation prevents full coverage.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nThis optimizes test selection, not production traffic. It must never infer that pairwise coverage proves full correctness, and it cannot silently add unsupported capabilities discovered from an unauthenticated target.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","coverage","combinatorial","testing"],"size":"l","title":"Generate compact pairwise call and event-sequence coverage"}	blake3:2PNuaVHW_Xz-vX9Rweo93BFqCdH-WpusaueKVXtBbGw
1784402222749978	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErBQ		item.create	bn-1pf	{"description":"Problem\nThe hardest practical barrier to SIPp is authoring a correct XML scenario for a real service with its exact headers, authentication challenge, SDP, timing, and teardown. Yet a working softphone call already contains most of that knowledge.\n\nOutcome\nAdd `sippycup learn CAPTURE --dialog SELECTOR --out PACK/` that synthesizes a reviewable, parameterized SIPp test pack from one authorized successful call, then validates the generated pack on loopback before it can target a network.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- Extract one dialog, classify local/remote roles, transactions, timing windows, optional responses, SDP changes, media assets, and teardown behavior.\n- Replace nondeterministic values—Call-ID, tags, Via branch, CSeq, Contact address, Content-Length, timestamps, SSRC, and media ports—with SIPp variables or generated values.\n- Convert Digest challenges into credential placeholders/reference names; remove captured Authorization values and warn when a safe authentication flow cannot be synthesized.\n- Produce annotated SIPp XML, injection CSV schema, expectation YAML, media fixtures, README, provenance hash, and a confidence/warning report showing every field kept, parameterized, or discarded.\n- Provide a canonical diff between the source dialog and generated behavior so reviewers can catch semantic drift.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- Golden fixtures for unauthenticated UDP, Digest challenge, provisional responses, CANCEL, remote BYE, and a re-INVITE generate deterministic packs.\n- No generated file contains the captured password, Authorization response, real phone identity, or an unapproved third-party address.\n- A generated baseline pack passes an isolated reference UAS/UAC replay and produces a PCAP accepted by its generated expectations.\n- Unsupported forks, proprietary encryption, ambiguous dialogs, or missing packets fail closed with precise manual steps rather than emitting unsafe replay material.\n- Generated XML passes a linter and all paths have explicit timeouts.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nInitial scope is a single complete dialog, not arbitrary multi-leg topology inference. Generated packs are drafts requiring review; the command never immediately replays traffic against the captured peer.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","scenario","automation","pcap"],"size":"xl","title":"Teach Sippycup a scenario from one successful call"}	blake3:TazKu-Kqry_RKmHa4ZME0wtHD92I_5yrdOQIUA1M9Bg
1784402240791815	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErBg		item.create	bn-2eu	{"description":"Problem\nA PCAP alone is difficult to reproduce, unsafe to share casually, and noisy to compare across runs because identifiers, ports, and timestamps change. Security findings need compact evidence that survives handoff.\n\nOutcome\nImplement `sippycup pack RUN_DIR` and `sippycup diff BASELINE CANDIDATE`. A pack is a self-describing, privacy-checked evidence artifact; a diff compares canonical signaling states and media measurements instead of raw bytes.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- Bundle the frozen campaign plan, UTC timeline, commands with secrets redacted, container image digest/SBOM, tool versions, SIPp stats, PCAP metadata, assertion JSON, operator notes/bookmarks, and selected logs.\n- Generate a manifest with path, media type, size, SHA-256, provenance, and sensitivity classification; optionally sign with minisign and encrypt for a named recipient.\n- Run a privacy linter that detects SIP Authorization material, phone/user identifiers, unexpected address ranges, decoded audio, and oversized captures. Require an explicit override for high-risk contents.\n- Canonicalize Call-IDs, tags, branches, CSeq offsets, ephemeral ports, SSRCs, and time origins before diffing. Compare state transitions, response classes/timings, negotiated media, endpoint topology, RTP quality, and assertion results.\n- Export concise Markdown plus versioned JSON and JUnit suitable for CI artifacts.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- Repacking identical normalized input is deterministic apart from an explicitly separated creation envelope.\n- `verify` detects any modified, missing, or unexpected file and validates optional signatures.\n- A fixture differing only in nondeterministic identifiers is equivalent; one-way media, new endpoint, codec change, slower setup, and post-BYE RTP produce focused diffs.\n- Secret-bearing fixtures are blocked by default and automated tests prove redaction never edits the source capture.\n- Bundle import works offline and does not require the original workspace.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nDo not promise reversible PCAP anonymization in the first release. Preserve originals read-only, distinguish omission from transformation, and never upload artifacts automatically.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","evidence","regression","privacy"],"size":"l","title":"Package tamper-evident evidence and golden-run diffs"}	blake3:Fi4IjBs1HtcWJ1fG47rxftqKXXT_JDhsLrHstYG9dnM
1784402260163800	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErBw		item.create	bn-lyg	{"description":"Problem\nReal calls encounter jitter, burst loss, reordering, duplication, bandwidth limits, MTU trouble, and asymmetric paths. Applying `tc` manually is dangerous with host networking and difficult to reproduce or clean up.\n\nOutcome\nAdd `sippycup chaos plan|run PROFILE -- CASE` that constructs a disposable network namespace around the test endpoint and applies named, seeded impairment profiles without touching host qdiscs by default.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- Build an isolated Podman/network-namespace topology with explicit ingress and egress interfaces. Use netem plus filters/IFB where supported; show a capability error rather than silently approximating unsupported directionality.\n- Ship reviewable profiles such as clean, office-Wi-Fi, burst-loss, constrained-uplink, high-jitter mobile, long-delay, reordering, duplication, MTU/fragmentation, and asymmetric-media.\n- Profile schema records delay distribution, jitter/correlation, loss model, reorder/duplicate/corrupt rates, bandwidth/queue, MTU, direction, seed, duration, and authorized target filter.\n- Snapshot qdiscs/routes before mutation, install cleanup traps, remove only objects created by the run, and verify restoration. Refuse host-network `NET_ADMIN` unless a separate dangerous-mode confirmation names a dedicated test VM.\n- Measure the actual packet distribution from capture and compare it with the requested profile.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- Automated tests prove default profiles alter only the disposable namespace and leave host qdiscs/routes byte-for-byte unchanged.\n- SIGINT, killed child processes, command failure, and repeated runs all clean up idempotently.\n- Seeded profiles are reproducible within documented kernel/timer tolerances; reports include requested versus observed delay/loss/reorder.\n- Target filters prevent impairment of unrelated traffic and aggregate campaign budgets still apply.\n- At least clean, fixed-delay, jitter, burst-loss, reorder, bandwidth, MTU, and asymmetric fixtures pass in CI where kernel capabilities permit.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nNo transparent changes to the workstation network, no default `--privileged`, and no claims of exact Internet simulation. Rootful/IFB-dependent capabilities must be isolated, explicit, and test-VM oriented.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","chaos","netem","safety"],"size":"l","title":"Create a disposable, guarded voice-network chaos lab"}	blake3:JXtJFMU4S0W4jhwqRyYl4TG1FE8boSq-uvo22iJgqBA
1784402282757036	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErCA		item.create	bn-3ka	{"description":"Problem\nBlind fuzzing produces noise, while happy-path calls miss parser and state-machine failures at the SIP/SDP/RTP boundary. Network-reachable robustness bugs need reproducible, minimal packets and strict traffic controls.\n\nOutcome\nImplement `sippycup torture plan|run|minimize` using curated standards-based cases plus bounded state-aware mutations. Start with RFC 4475 SIP torture messages, then add focused SDP, RTP, RFC 4733, and RTCP edge cases relevant to a direct media terminator.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- Curate bit-exact valid and invalid cases with expected response class or acceptable outcomes; preserve provenance and case IDs.\n- Establish the minimum required dialog state, inject one mutation, observe response/liveness, then run a clean recovery canary. Mutations target length disagreements, duplicate/folded headers, extreme-but-bounded values, transaction/tag/CSeq anomalies, SDP media/address contradictions, RTP sequence/timestamp/SSRC/payload transitions, and malformed RTCP blocks.\n- Enforce immutable per-run caps for packets, bytes, cases, rate, concurrency, duration, and consecutive failures. Stop immediately on operator signal, target health callback, recovery-canary failure, or configured server metric.\n- On a reproducible failure, use hierarchical delta debugging to remove headers, body sections, and mutation dimensions while preserving the outcome across a configurable quorum such as 3 of 5 attempts.\n- Save a standalone reproducer, exact bytes, capture frames, expected versus actual behavior, and minimized provenance.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- Every corpus item has a reviewable description and an isolated reference fixture proving the harness sends the intended bytes.\n- Default mode sends one case at a time at a low rate and cannot perform credential guessing, reflection, spoofing, or unbounded payload expansion.\n- Injected parser/state failures trigger the recovery gate and stop further cases.\n- The minimizer demonstrably reduces composite fixtures while retaining the same classified outcome and never crosses the original traffic budget.\n- Dry-run prints the complete corpus selection, state prerequisites, and maximum traffic before sending anything.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nAuthorized staging only. This is network protocol robustness testing, not Rust/process fuzzing, volumetric denial-of-service, user enumeration, or authentication cracking.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","security","robustness","fuzzing"],"size":"xl","title":"Add state-aware protocol torture tests with automatic minimization"}	blake3:d8ak2-fKk9qGwuTUWdgTig7_HcOvkGx47sSKVd71DNI
1784402303306434	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErCQ		item.create	bn-1yq	{"description":"Problem\nA fixed SIPp load test either stays too low to reveal the useful limit or overshoots into avoidable disruption. For a direct RTP service, the meaningful boundary combines call success, setup latency, active media quality, and recovery—not raw requests per second.\n\nOutcome\nAdd `sippycup envelope plan|run` for bounded adaptive ramps. It estimates the first sustainable degradation knee under an owner-approved ceiling, backs off automatically, and measures recovery with clean canary calls.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- Begin from a low baseline, ramp one dimension at a time (CPS, concurrent calls, or media packet rate), and hold each level long enough for stable observations.\n- Consume SIPp counters/response-time distributions, PCAP assertions, RTP loss/jitter, socket errors, and optional read-only health adapters such as Prometheus queries or a user-provided command returning JSON.\n- Use conservative sequential/change-point logic: require repeated evidence before declaring degradation, but immediately stop for hard thresholds such as recovery-canary failure, timeout rate, 5xx rate, media loss, latency, or server health.\n- After a trigger, stop new calls, allow bounded teardown, wait a configured cooldown, and place periodic one-call canaries until recovery or the recovery deadline.\n- Report the tested envelope, uncertainty, knee interval, trigger evidence, hysteresis, recovery time, and censored result when the authorization ceiling was reached first.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- The manifest requires hard maxima for CPS, concurrency, packets/second, total calls, duration, and cooldown; command-line flags can only lower them.\n- A synthetic degrading endpoint causes backoff before the hard ceiling and a healthy endpoint stops cleanly at the authorized ceiling.\n- SIGINT and health-adapter failure stop new traffic immediately and still attempt safe teardown/evidence capture.\n- Repeated seeded runs produce comparable knee intervals; the report never calls an untested value “capacity”.\n- Baseline and post-test canaries distinguish load failure from failure to recover.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nNo autonomous stress against production, no distributed load generation initially, and no attempt to defeat rate limits. The objective is a defensible bounded envelope, not maximum possible traffic.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","load","resilience","safety"],"size":"l","title":"Find the safe capacity knee and prove recovery"}	blake3:rcmrkduCfdN3uPZnst23ynMxxmne8rgvw3CCODGslRk
1784402323976347	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErCg		item.create	bn-2nj	{"description":"Problem\nDuring a live call test the operator currently juggles tcpdump, SIPp, TShark/Termshark, notes, budgets, and cleanup across terminals. Important events are easy to miss, and stopping safely should never require remembering process IDs.\n\nOutcome\nAdd `sippycup ui MANIFEST` as a keyboard-driven mission-control view over the campaign event stream. It should make safe execution understandable to a phone-system newcomer while retaining precise drill-down for an expert.\n\nImplementation sketch\n- Pre-run view shows frozen targets, authorization/budget summary, planned cases, capabilities, unresolved warnings, and the exact point at which traffic begins.\n- Live view shows current/next case, UTC timer, remaining calls/packets/duration, capture state and size, SIP ladder/status counters, per-direction RTP packets/loss/jitter, negotiated codecs/endpoints, recovery-canary status, and high-signal assertion warnings.\n- Provide explicit keys for start, pause new calls, graceful stop, emergency stop, case skip, timestamped note/bookmark, and opening the current capture in Termshark. Dangerous actions require confirmation; stop is always immediate and prominent.\n- Render from structured events/results rather than parsing ANSI output. Maintain a noninteractive JSON mode with identical semantics for CI and accessibility.\n- Store notes as separate metadata, not packet edits, and include bookmarks in the evidence pack.\n\nAcceptance criteria\n- A first-time user can plan, start one loopback call, identify both media directions, add a note, stop, and locate the report using only in-app guidance.\n- Terminal resize, lost child process, assertion failure, SIGINT, and non-TTY execution are handled without corrupting the run or losing cleanup.\n- Budget counters are derived from executed events and never show more remaining traffic than the safety gate permits.\n- Golden snapshot tests cover plan, running, warning, stopping, recovery, and complete states; keyboard help is always one key away.\n- The UI remains responsive while TShark/SIPp emit heavy output by using bounded queues and backpressure.\n\nGuardrails / non-goals\nThe TUI orchestrates existing tested primitives; it does not become a second protocol engine. No browser dashboard or multi-user control plane in the first version, and no hidden auto-start behavior.","kind":"goal","labels":["roadmap","tui","ux","observability"],"size":"xl","title":"Unify testing in a live mission-control TUI"}	blake3:isppJ1tjCMdJ2K2j2f4n2Pcp5Fk-lJkBZ_AhrWNir4w
