1784492223039300	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErpQI		item.move	bn-3jx	{"reason":"Offline advisor, schema, docs, safety tests, smoke coverage, and private engagement evidence are complete.","state":"done"}	blake3:ZxtLnBsKER7rIJAY9Kv-gaKa4RVy1hKxHLoXLx8toGI
1784496806365647	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErpgI		item.create	bn-3kt	{"description":"# Context & Background\nSippycup currently exposes a mixture of top-level aliases, sibling host scripts, and exact in-image binary names. Most capabilities are technically reachable, but users must already know implementation details; ./bin/sippycup --help fails, and natural forms such as sippycup torture, chaos, and ui do not resolve.\n\n# Goal\nMake bin/sippycup the documented, discoverable, stable entrypoint for every operator-facing workflow while preserving the host/container execution boundary, authorization gates, and an explicit advanced pass-through escape hatch.\n\n# Design Direction\nUse a declarative command registry as the source of truth for aliases, execution location, help text, capability requirements, and safety classification. Keep internal helper binaries available for development and backward compatibility, but remove any need for ordinary users to invoke them directly.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Every operator-facing capability is reachable through a natural sippycup subcommand.\n- [ ] sippycup help and per-command help work without requiring a container runtime where possible.\n- [ ] Host-only and container-only commands retain their correct execution semantics.\n- [ ] Existing scripts continue to work during a documented compatibility window.\n- [ ] Documentation consistently teaches the single entrypoint.\n- [ ] A network-free exit gate proves routing, help, failure behavior, and safety invariants.\n\n# Project Value\nA single front door makes the open-source toolbox approachable, scriptable, and supportable without hiding the security boundaries that make it safe.","kind":"goal","labels":["cli","ux","architecture"],"parent":"bn-22t","size":"xl","title":"Unify Sippycup behind one discoverable CLI"}	blake3:THZjGGBvDjDzsjdyMG0H9NWVqoddQRB-pU2qv7AUMpg
1784496854321595	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErpwI		item.create	bn-2ns	{"description":"# Context\nRouting is currently encoded as ad hoc Bash conditionals, so aliases, help, execution location, and safety properties can drift.\n\n# Implementation Approach\nDefine one auditable registry for public command name, aliases, host/direct/container execution mode, backing executable, summary, runtime requirement, capability class, and whether the command can generate network traffic. Refactor bin/sippycup to resolve commands through it without eval or unsafe word splitting. Define reserved launcher options and the behavior of no arguments, --, help, and unknown commands.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Registry covers every operator-facing command and intentionally classifies internal helpers.\n- [ ] Duplicate names and aliases fail a static validation test.\n- [ ] Dispatch uses fixed argv arrays and preserves exact user arguments.\n- [ ] Unknown commands return exit 2 with a useful suggestion and no container launch.\n- [ ] No-argument behavior and the advanced pass-through contract are documented.\n\n# Project Value\nThis becomes the stable foundation for one entrypoint and prevents future features from becoming undiscoverable siblings.","kind":"task","labels":["cli","architecture"],"parent":"bn-3kt","size":"m","title":"Define the unified command registry and routing contract"}	blake3:80RnshPr-DEaNTVd2ANH4-QYSMH0MIIdGWNSYM3beOM
1784496854476182	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErqAI		item.create	bn-3ug	{"description":"# Context\ncapture, preflight, report, selftest, and chaos-exit-gate are separate host scripts. Their host privileges, paths, and orchestration semantics must not be accidentally converted into generic in-container execution.\n\n# Implementation Approach\nAdd natural subcommands backed by the existing host wrappers: sippycup capture, preflight, report, selftest, and chaos-exit-gate. Preserve dry-run defaults and current exit codes. Normalize help handling and resolve project-relative paths consistently. Keep the sibling scripts as compatibility shims rather than duplicating logic.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Each host workflow is callable through bin/sippycup with unchanged safety behavior.\n- [ ] --help for every host workflow is network-free and exits zero.\n- [ ] Capture and preflight dry-run tests prove no socket or sudo side effect.\n- [ ] Argument quoting, signals, and child exit codes propagate correctly.\n- [ ] Existing direct script invocations remain functional.\n\n# Project Value\nUsers gain one command surface without weakening the host-specific controls around capture and network preparation.","kind":"task","labels":["cli","host","workflows"],"parent":"bn-3kt","size":"m","title":"Fold host-side workflows into sippycup subcommands"}	blake3:mIzhEBSM-jUT63_3cBOwsOoEedKWQcZnjoKBumNI3z0
1784496854639596	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErqQI		item.create	bn-3b9	{"description":"# Context\nCampaign is reachable naturally, but torture, chaos, UI, evidence, pack, and diff currently require internal sippycup-* binary names. Media echo and container diagnostics are similarly obscure.\n\n# Implementation Approach\nRoute concise names to fixed in-image executables: campaign, torture, chaos, ui, evidence, pack, diff, media-echo, and other genuinely operator-facing families found by the registry audit. Preserve shell as an explicit command and retain -- COMMAND as an advanced arbitrary-command escape hatch. Do not expose implementation-only runners as public commands.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Every public in-image family has a concise, documented alias.\n- [ ] Natural aliases and legacy exact binary forms return equivalent help and exit codes.\n- [ ] Runtime selection and capability flags remain centralized in the launcher.\n- [ ] Internal campaign runners, container preflight helpers, and smoke internals are classified but omitted from normal help.\n- [ ] Missing image/runtime failures name the requested command and remediation.\n\n# Project Value\nThe toolbox feels like one product instead of a collection of binaries while retaining expert escape hatches.","kind":"task","labels":["cli","container","aliases"],"parent":"bn-3kt","size":"m","title":"Add natural aliases for all container tool families"}	blake3:0vkK7FWmOBvaESEdz3ifW5rQKed_pXjtif1IeRdpJpA
1784496854800848	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErqgI		item.create	bn-3vq	{"description":"# Context\nsippycup --help currently fails before launch, and there is no command index or indication of which workflows need a container, privileges, authorization, or network access.\n\n# Implementation Approach\nGenerate stable help from the command registry. Support sippycup help, --help, help COMMAND, COMMAND --help, and --version. Group commands by preparation, execution, analysis, evidence, resilience, and advanced use. Annotate execution location and network/safety class without overwhelming the first screen. Add typo suggestions with deterministic matching.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Global help works with PATH stripped of Podman, nerdctl, and Docker.\n- [ ] Every documented public command appears exactly once.\n- [ ] Per-command help never sends traffic and invokes no privileged operation.\n- [ ] Help clearly distinguishes planning/offline commands from potentially network-active commands.\n- [ ] Human and stable machine-readable command listings are available.\n\n# Project Value\nOpen-source users can discover capabilities safely without reading source code or memorizing binary names.","kind":"task","labels":["cli","help","ux"],"parent":"bn-3kt","size":"m","title":"Build offline global help, command discovery, and version output"}	blake3:yTywYuNQkWSV8Zh8eiFAp91fLckIuSogy04IOzFQmAc
1784496854955319	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErqwI		item.create	bn-31r	{"description":"# Context\nExisting documentation, automation, and users may invoke bin/capture, bin/preflight, campaign, or sippycup-* tools directly. Consolidation must not create a flag day.\n\n# Implementation Approach\nInventory supported legacy entrypoints, keep thin shims where appropriate, and define which internal binaries are intentionally unsupported. Avoid warnings that pollute machine-readable stdout. Document a compatibility window and test legacy/new equivalence for argv, exit status, and relevant output contracts.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Existing supported entrypoints continue to work after consolidation.\n- [ ] JSON and JUnit stdout remain byte-clean.\n- [ ] Deprecation messages, if any, go to stderr and are suppressible.\n- [ ] Public versus internal executables are explicitly documented.\n- [ ] No symlink or wrapper recursion is possible.\n\n# Project Value\nThe new UX can ship safely without breaking established scripts or integrations.","kind":"task","labels":["cli","compatibility"],"parent":"bn-3kt","size":"s","title":"Preserve direct-script compatibility and define deprecation policy"}	blake3:FloJlw2VClPB5Z6uditTyv8D-e-VphlB8YhsC8dGzD8
1784496855120304	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErrAI		item.create	bn-dsc	{"description":"# Context\nREADME and deep documentation currently mix bin/sippycup aliases, sibling scripts, bare in-image tools, and sippycup-* implementation names. That teaches the architecture instead of the product.\n\n# Implementation Approach\nUpdate README, workflow guides, examples, and copy-paste snippets to use bin/sippycup consistently. Retain direct binary names only in an advanced/internal reference. Add a compact command map and explain host versus container execution, dry-run planning, authorization, and the -- escape hatch.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] All ordinary operator examples use the unified entrypoint.\n- [ ] Every copied command resolves and its --help succeeds.\n- [ ] Links and renamed examples remain valid.\n- [ ] Documentation never implies that command reachability grants target authorization.\n- [ ] A repository check prevents new public docs from introducing unsupported sibling invocation forms.\n\n# Project Value\nConsistent documentation makes the unified CLI real for users rather than merely an implementation option.","kind":"task","labels":["docs","examples","ux"],"parent":"bn-3kt","size":"m","title":"Migrate documentation and examples to the single entrypoint"}	blake3:yBAeywSaRydtV7iFIin3HVRgO669VSKkVeDCw8p73do
1784496855276088	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErrQI		item.create	bn-1as	{"description":"# Context\nA routing refactor can silently alter capabilities, network namespaces, mounts, argument boundaries, output contracts, or failure behavior. A dedicated gate is required before declaring one-entrypoint coverage complete.\n\n# Implementation Approach\nBuild a table-driven, network-free contract suite from the registry. Exercise global/per-command help, direct host dispatch, direct Python dispatch, container aliases under fake and real runtimes, legacy equivalence, unknown commands, absent runtime/image, signals, quoting, and exit codes. Add a container smoke assertion and a completeness check comparing public registry entries with packaged executables.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Every public registry command has a passing routing/help test.\n- [ ] Tests prove help, discovery, and dry-run paths make zero target network calls.\n- [ ] Podman, nerdctl, Docker, explicit runtime, and missing-runtime selection paths are covered with fakes; the available real runtime passes smoke.\n- [ ] Capability, network, volume, and host/container placement match the reviewed contract.\n- [ ] Full test suite, shell/static checks, image build, and smoke pass.\n- [ ] Goal closes only when no operator-facing sibling command lacks a unified route.\n\n# Project Value\nThe gate turns “single entrypoint” into a durable invariant instead of a one-time documentation claim.","kind":"task","labels":["exit-gate","cli","safety","testing"],"parent":"bn-3kt","size":"m","title":"Exit gate the unified CLI across host and container runtimes"}	blake3:a00H8F7ZrncsNAF6bplldf_MyBFEClJfboXIKFe5UQ0
1784496864206466	bob-dev	itc:v3:AWKc55JPnzzNAAAAAAAAQbu9V997YAAAAAErrgI		item.link	bn-3ug	{"link_type":"blocks","target":"bn-2ns"}	blake3:JovjepMCbec_LkBfalYsoD5-Tg-sJcrEdEz_hNZ1uAw
